  "What is a limit in calculus?": "",
  "The value a function approaches as the input approaches a particular value, even if the function is not defined there": "",
  "The area under a curve between two points": "",
  "The slope of the tangent line to a curve at a given point": "",
  "The maximum value a function can reach on its domain": "",
  "A limit describes the value that f(x) approaches as x approaches a specific value c, written lim(x->c) f(x) = L. The function need not be defined or equal to L at x = c.": "",
  "What does it mean for a function to be continuous at a point?": "",
  "The function has a derivative at that point": "",
  "The function has no vertical asymptote anywhere in its domain": "",
  "The function is defined at that point, the limit exists there, and the limit equals the function value": "",
  "The function is increasing at that point": "",
  "Continuity at x = c requires three conditions: (1) f(c) is defined, (2) lim(x->c) f(x) exists, and (3) lim(x->c) f(x) = f(c). All three must hold simultaneously.": "",
  "What is a one-sided limit?": "",
  "A limit where x approaches a value only from the left or only from the right": "",
  "A limit that exists for only one function": "",
  "A limit where the function approaches exactly one output": "",
  "A limit that can only equal positive values": "",
  "A one-sided limit considers the behavior of f(x) as x approaches c from only one direction: lim(x->c^-) from the left or lim(x->c^+) from the right.": "",
  "What does the Intermediate Value Theorem state?": "",
  "If f is continuous on [a,b] and k is between f(a) and f(b), then there exists at least one c in (a,b) with f(c) = k": "",
  "The derivative of a continuous function is always positive": "",
  "A continuous function on a closed interval must have a maximum and minimum value": "",
  "Every polynomial function has at least one real root": "",
  "The IVT guarantees that a continuous function on [a,b] takes on every value between f(a) and f(b) at some point c in the open interval (a,b).": "",
  "What is a removable discontinuity?": "",
  "A discontinuity that cannot be eliminated by any redefinition": "",
  "A discontinuity where the function approaches infinity": "",
  "A discontinuity where the function jumps from one value to another": "",
  "A discontinuity where the limit exists but the function is either undefined or does not equal the limit at that point": "",
  "A removable discontinuity occurs when lim(x->c) f(x) exists but f(c) is undefined or f(c) does not equal the limit. It can be 'removed' by redefining f(c) to equal the limit.": "",
  "What does 'lim(x->c) f(x) = L' mean in the epsilon-delta sense?": "",
  "f(x) equals L for all x near c within the broader context of delta analysis": "",
  "For every epsilon > 0, there exists a delta > 0 such that if 0 < |x - c| < delta, then |f(x) - L| < epsilon": "",
  "The graph of f passes through the point (c, L), especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "f(c) = L exactly because conventional analysis of delta suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "The formal epsilon-delta definition states that for every epsilon > 0 there exists delta > 0 such that whenever 0 < |x - c| < delta, we have |f(x) - L| < epsilon, meaning f(x) can be made arbitrarily close to L.": "",
